text:
Your entire life, you've been told you're deathly allergic to bees. You've always had people protecting you from them, be it your mother or a hired hand. Today, one slips through and lands on your shoulder. You hear a tiny voice say "Your Majesty, what are your orders?"

Trigger warning: Violence,  AI portrayal of mental illness

I jump, startled. "It's a bee, get it off me!" I scream, as I run to the servants on the deck.  I knock over the small woman who was standing behind me.  I didn't even notice her before. "Stand still", the maid says in her tiny voice, as she grab a towel. "We'll just get it off you, and then you can go back to your party." 

"No, no, no, I can't be near it!" I scream. The maid flicks the bee with the towel, and it flies off. "Oh, thank you, thank you, I can't believe you got it off me." I say, as I run back to the party. 

"That was weird", I hear the maid say. "I've never seen someone react like that to a bee before."
"I'm not surprised", the other maid says. "She's always been a bit of a weirdo." She leans conspiratorially close. "She is on a new medication, and has been hearing voices lately" "I heard that too", the first maid says.

I leap to my feet. There is no way I will let servants talk to me like that! I run back to the deck, and grab the first maid by the hair. "How dare you talk about me like that!" I scream, as I pull her to the ground. "I am the queen, and you will show me respect!" 

"I'm sorry, Your Majesty", the maid says, as she tries to get up. I kick her in the stomach, and she falls back to the ground. "I'm sorry, I'm sorry, I'm sorry!" she screams. 

"I'm not done with you yet", I say, as I grab her by the neck. "You will never disrespect me again, or I will have you executed." I let go of her, and she crawls away. "Now, I'm going back to my party." 

I walk back to the party, and the guests are all staring at me. "What are you looking at?" I say. "I was just teaching a servant a lesson." 
"I think you should go back to your room", my husband says. "You've been acting really strange lately." 
"I'm fine, I'm fine", I say. "I'm just going to go get a drink." 

I walk over to the bar, and the bartender hands me a drink. I don't notice that my husband has my meds in hand, and slips them into my drink. I take a sip, and I feel a wave of calm wash over me. I feel so much better, so much more relaxed.
